WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.480
 - Welcome to C Programming for Everybody.

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:03.660
 My name's Charles Severance,

00:00:03.660 --> 00:00:05.900
 and I'm your instructor for this course.

00:00:05.900 --> 00:00:08.120
 This course and website is dedicated to learning

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:10.240
 the classic version of C programming language

00:00:10.240 --> 00:00:14.060
 from the 1978 book written by Brian W. Kernigan

00:00:14.060 --> 00:00:15.800
 and Dennis M. Ritchie.

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:17.840
 This book places the reader in the middle

00:00:17.840 --> 00:00:20.800
 of the 1970s transition from a hardware-centered

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:23.740
 computer science to a focus on writing portable

00:00:23.740 --> 00:00:25.520
 and efficient software.

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:27.780
 C was used to develop operating systems

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:30.480
 like Unix, Minix, and Linux.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:33.360
 Programming languages like Perl, Python, Java,

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:36.480
 and JavaScript and Ruby are all written in C.

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:39.920
 Software like early TCP/IP networking stack implementations

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:42.720
 that made the internet possible were written in C.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:45.120
 And the first web browsers and web servers

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:46.420
 were written in C.

00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:50.160
 Writing software in C enabled major advances

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:52.640
 in computer architecture and performance.

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:54.720
 Operating systems, compilers, and utilities

00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:57.640
 could be recompiled to work on a new hardware platform

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:00.680
 once we had a C compiler for the new hardware.

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:02.720
 So much software has been written in C

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:06.080
 over the past 40 years that there's a very good chance

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:08.920
 that much of the software that you use every day

00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:12.480
 was either written in C or written in a programming language

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:14.700
 that was written in C.

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:16.960
 So we study C less as a programming language

00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:19.760
 to use on a daily basis and more as the foundation

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:22.020
 of modern software and computing.

00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:24.660
 In many ways, C is the technology equivalent

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:27.280
 of the Rosetta Stone in that it provides a connection

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:29.800
 between the programming languages of the past

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:32.280
 and the programming languages of the present.

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:37.080
 The name CC4E in www.cc4e.com

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:40.320
 refers to the original Unix command CC,

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:42.040
 which was the command that you used

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:43.920
 to compile your C program.

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:48.320
 CC stood for C compiler and it is featured on the first page

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:51.380
 of the first chapter of the KNRC book.

00:01:51.380 --> 00:01:54.360
 Programmers like me from the 1970s and 1980s

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:58.960
 type CC on Unix systems like the AT&T 3B2

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:03.040
 to compile and run their first Hello World program in C.

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:06.080
 This material is being presented under fair use

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:08.440
 as we are making use of material from a copyrighted work

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:10.520
 that is out of print and not broadly available

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:11.680
 in any format.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:14.880
 The book is also not available in any accessible format.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:16.360
 We are making use of this material

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:18.000
 in a teaching and research context

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:20.380
 with a focus on studying its contribution

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:22.240
 to computing history.

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:24.440
 The material is available for free and online

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:26.320
 to anyone who wants to learn about the history

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:30.280
 of the C language, computing, and computer architecture.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:31.520
 Welcome to the course.

